After you meet the requirements and assign roles to users, set up service accounts. Service accounts save information about your cloud provider accounts, including the credentials necessary to access the account. 

Navigate to Cloud Provisioning and Governance > Service Accounts to create a new service account. 

See the following topics for additional information:

  • Create an AWS Service Account
  • Create an MS Azure Service Principal and Add an Azure Service Account
  • Create a Service Account for VMware
  • Create a Service Account for Google Cloud Platform
  • Create a Service Account for IBM Cloud

false cmdb_ci_cloud_service_account_list.do?sysparm_userpref_module=ac88c1ddeb232200979aa5115206fe8c&sysparm_clear_stack=true&sysparm_clear_stack=true 1 1 5264a357db2c32006f767bedae96196c false true Fill out these form fields. Note the different types of Account IDs for the relevant cloud provider: 

 Field 

 Description

 Name 

 Enter a descriptive name for the account. 

 Account ID 

 Enter the account ID to which this credential belongs: 

  • For AWS, use the 12-digit account number. 
  • For Azure, the account ID is the subscription ID. 
  • For VMWare: the account ID is the instance UUID.  

 Discovery credentials 

 Create the credentials required to manage this account. 

 Datacenter URL 

 Enter the URL for the datacenter. This is mandatory for VMware vCenter datacenters. 

 The URL must be the full URL, for example, https://<IP-of-vCenter/sdk> 

 Datacenter type 

 Select the table from the CMDB that represents the type of datacenter. 

 Datacenter discovery status 

 The last execution of datacenter discovery. 


  • Parent account: Appears when you select AWS datacenter
    • Select the AWS main account that represents the Organization in AWS that this member account belongs to.
    • Leave the field empty if this account is not part of an AWS Organization
  • Is main account: Appears when you select AWS datacenter
    • Clear the check box if the account is not the Organization account.
    • Select the check box to associate the AWS cloud service account with the main account. The main account corresponds to the Organization in AWS. You can identify any cloud service account in your instance as a main account only if you already configured the account in AWS as an Organization and you already associated other accounts under the Organization. See the AWS documentation for information on Organizations.

To obtain the UUID for the VMWare account ID, do one of the following:  

 

  • Open the managed object browser for the vCenter, and then click content about. Copy the value of the instanceUuid property. 
  • If you have already run Discovery on your VMWare infrastructure, you can open the Cloud API Trail, and then filter the list of records where Method name = ListDatacenters. Find the relevant record, and then open the CAPI Trail Log record from the related list. The UUID is the value of the locationid in the Log value field.
